/// A "fetch_add"-like operation implemented by protecting a non-atomic
/// read-modify-write sequence with a critical section.
///
/// IMPORTANT NOTES (re: the original embedded question):
///
/// 1) Once you're inside `critical_section::with`, the *mutual exclusion*
///    (i.e. no concurrent access) is provided by the critical section mechanism,
///    not by atomic ordering.
///
///    Therefore, using `Ordering::Relaxed` for the atomic load/store is fine
///    *as long as every access that participates in the synchronization is also
///    performed under the same critical section*.
///
///    In that case, the atomic is basically just being used as an integer cell
///    type; the ordering doesn't carry the synchronization.
///
/// 2) If, however, you rely on this counter to also establish ordering with
///    other memory operations (Acquire/Release semantics), then you need to
///    reason about that separately. A `fetch_add(Relaxed)` never provided such
///    ordering anyway—only atomicity.
///
/// 3) On RP2040 specifically: disabling interrupts on one core does NOT stop the
///    other core. So a critical section implementation must also provide
///    *cross-core* exclusion (e.g., via the RP2040 hardware spinlocks) if the
///    counter is shared between cores.
///
///    The `critical-section` crate is just an abstraction; whether it is safe
///    across cores depends on the platform-specific impl you use.
fn fetch_add_via_critical_section(x: &AtomicUsize, inc: usize) -> usize {
